I think it was GE who made a sort of thin shroud and built the generator into the outer shroud allowing greater power output at lower wind speeds for smaller scale turbines.

@ThinkingandTinkering 
Ok good.  Thanks.  
At what point are you using the anemometer?  At the outlet of the blower nozzle or just before the windmill?   If it's at the blower nozzle, are you using the area of the nozzle to determine your calculations?  That would be the most accurate determination of air imput power, but unfortunately, the calculation of output power gets muddied by how well the wind is distributed across the larger surface area of the windmill.   I suspect the cone efficiently distributes that narrow airstream to the most efficient parts of the windmill.   However, when comparing efficiencies in an airstream that would be large enough to cover the entire windmill, like natural wind would be, the cone may not be as beneficial and may even rob some useable blade surface area because the spoon handles would otherwise catch some wind as well.
